If you are a newcomer to Cincinnati, you may have wondered
why there are "three" political parties in City Council elections
. . . Republicans, Democrats and the City Charter Committee.
The "Charterites" are a widely respected group on the Amer
ican political scene, with roots deepen Cincinnati history.
From the turn of the century till 1925. Cincinnati was ac
knowledged to be the WORST governed city in the county.
Graft, corruption, vice were everywhere, controlled by a tyran
nical Republican machine in the true "boss" tradition. In 1924
a group of courageous citizens, including BOTH Republicans
and Democrats, rose up against this corrupt political machine.
They called themselves the City Charter Committee. They
wrote a new city charter, fought for its adoption, installed the
city manager system, eliminated politics and favoritism from
city employment and city contracts, and balanced the city
By 1957 after 33 years of Charter influence Fortune Maga
zine was describing Cincinnati as "the best governed city in
the U.S." Charles P. Taft, leader of the Charter majority
and Cincinnati's fifth Charter Mayor, was described as "one
of the best mayors in U.S. history."
If you are a straight party voter, read no further . . this mes
sage is really not for you. But if you are open-minded and
consider yourself a political "independent" who votes for prin
ciples ... not party labels .,.we ask you to join the more than
10,000 independent-minded Cincinnati citizens who make up
Because Charter is a purely LOCAL political organization
. . . concerned only with the Council of the City of Cincinnati
... its candidates can make decisions with complete independ
ence. They needn't fear that a stand on a city issue will cause
the political party embarrassment in the county, or state. As a
result the Charter Councilmen have taken strong and cour
ageous positions on issues like annexation of county territory
to the city while the opposition, who must please both county
and city politicians, evade the issue altogether, or take feeble
stands to avoid losing votes for the party.
The Issue In Next Tuesday's Election
In the coming election on next Tuesday, the issue is clear.
Will Cincinnati get action on the vital problems of hous
ing, traffic, mass transportation, downtown decay, inter-group
relations and metropolitan government? Or, will there fee the
usual political promises measured out at regular intervals by the
present Republican majority. Look at the record of the past
four years Republican inaction, inability to face the issues
that take courage and imagination to tackle and solve relo
cation housing, zone code revisions, mass transit, central busi
ness and riverfront redevelopment. ACTION or just political
promises that's the issue that's the choice you as a voter
Local political groups calling themselves "Democrats" or
"Republicans" always try to "ride the coattails" of the na
tional parties for prestige and respectability. A voter must look
behind the national party label, however, and judge each
LOCAL group for what IT REALLY IS to get a true
understanding of what he's voting for.
We point out with regret that the local Republican organiza
tion which runs candidates for Cincinnati City Council is really
the Hamilton County organization. Its interests are often con
flictingbetween city and county. It's a fact, never denied,
that Republican county employees, in one way or another, must
."kick back" at least 2Vz of their total salaries to the Re
publican organization treasury. Further, county Republicans
, have not held a competitive examination for county job holders
or applicants in years ... in flagrant violation of State Civil
Service requirements. County workers are in danger of losing
, their jobs if they do not obey their political bosses. This is the
Republican organization that endorses and supports the Re
For years . . . until 1957 . . . there were only TWO political
parties entered in the Council race ... the Charterites and the
machine Republicans. However, in 1959. a faction of the
Democrats led by disappointed job and patronage seekers,
decided they no longer wanted to cooperate with the Charter
Committee for non-partisan good government and wanted, in
stead, to build a local party machine like the Republicans.
So. now there are THREE political parties . . . making it
thoroughly confusing for the average voter to know what choice
to make. The Democrats have riot only proved that they are
badly split . . . that two of their candidates are in complete
opposition to the party chieftains ... but also have demon
strated their willingness to employ trickery and deceit in gath
ering signatures to propose an issue on the ballot that they
themselves were AGAINST. The Enquirer and Post and
Times-Star exposed, and the courts nullified, this transparent
attempt to play political football with one of the most signifi
cant problems facing the city today: what to do with our
decaying "core" area. The Democrats, in using such a vital
issue for party politics. ALMOST COST THE CITY

of nine outstanding candidates for City Council . . . Cincinnati
citizens with impressive records of city service in fields ranging
from government to medicine. These people are not "politi
cians" but dedicated, hard-working citizens who believe in the
future of their city, want to work for their city and who will
devote two years of their lives to the city. Their records of
achievement and action encompass their whole lives. These
